Read consistency and secondary indexes.

DynamoDB writes are committed to multiple availability zones before they acknowledge, and reads come in three consistency levels that trade consistency against cost. Eventually consistent, the default, may be stale by up to about a second, and costs half a read-capacity-unit; it's fine for most reads. Strongly consistent always returns the latest committed write, and costs one full read-capacity-unit; use it when you've just written and need to read your own write. And transactional gives you A-C-I-D guarantees across multiple items or tables, at twice the cost again. The pattern: read eventually-consistent by default, use strongly-consistent only where the application logic requires it, and reserve transactions for the small set of operations with a genuine multi-item invariant, like financial or inventory operations.

Secondary indexes let one table answer more access patterns by maintaining a second copy of items keyed differently. A Local Secondary Index, or L-S-I, keeps the base table's partition key but uses a different sort key, like "same customer, ordered by date". L-S-Is must be defined at table creation, you get up to five, they share the base table's throughput, they support strongly-consistent reads, and every partition key is capped at ten gigabytes. A Global Secondary Index, or G-S-I, uses a different partition key, and optionally a different sort key, like "all orders where status equals shipped, ordered by date". G-S-Is can be created or dropped at any time, up to twenty by default, they have their own separate throughput, and they're eventually consistent only.

The rule: the G-S-I is the default, because it's flexible and you can add it any time; reach for an L-S-I only when you need strong consistency on an alternate sort within the same partition, and remember you must plan L-S-Is up front.
